Jim Hughes

Wednesday, 5 July 2017

Check NAs for non-binned data

any(is.na(rawiv$Sample.ID))
[1] FALSE
any(is.na(rawiv$Time..min.))
[1] TRUE

There are NAs in the time column, this could be problematic. Identify where the NAs are located

rawiv[which(is.na(rawiv$Dose..mg.kg.)), ]
rawiv[which(is.na(rawiv$Mouse.Wt..g.)), ]
rawiv[which(is.na(rawiv$Time..min.)), ]

NAs appear to be as a result of a repeat sample, it was ascertained from correspondence with Mitch that these are in fact for the same mouse. These data entries will need to be combined into a single data entry.

Count number of samples (including repeats mentioned above)

length(unique(rawiv$Sample.ID))
[1] 172

Clean & Extract Data

Data converted to following units:

  • Dose - mg
  • AMT - ng
  • Weight - g
  • Concentrations - ng/mL
  • Time - min

Sample IDs cleaned up using function that splits the ID string into ID and nominal time after dose (TADNOM).

head(dataiv)
IDiv <- end.splitter(dataiv$ID)
dataiv <- cbind(IDiv, dataiv[,-1])
head(dataiv)

Check the nominal time against dose.

with(dataiv, table(DOSEMGKG, TADNOM))
        TADNOM
DOSEMGKG 2 10 20 25 45 60 90 180 300 480
     0.5 5  5  0  5  5  5  5   5   5   0
     1.5 5  5  5  0  5  5  5   5   5   0
     5   5  5  5  0  5  5  5   5   5   5
     10  5  5  5  0  5  5  5   5   5   5
dataiv[which(dataiv$TADNOM == "25"), ]

There are one set of values stated to have TADNOM as 25, but values were measured at 20mins, one at 13 which is odd. The TADNOM is likely meant to be 20, and since this data will only be used for categorising the data the TADNOM was changed to 20 for these rows.

The string splitting function identify the repeated sample with a repeated UID. There are two lots of concentrations in these rows, so which one is correct?

subiv <- dataiv[which(with(dataiv, TADNOM == "20" & DOSEMGKG == 5 & !is.na(dataiv$WT))), ]
IDori <- dataiv[which(is.na(dataiv$WT)), ]
IDrep <- arrange(dataiv[which(is.na(dataiv$DOSEMGKG)), ], UID)
tissue.mean <- function(x) {
  colwise(mean)(x[c("PLA", "BRA", "LVR", "MSC", "HRT", "SPL", "LUN", "KID")])
}
rbind(tissue.mean(subiv), tissue.mean(IDori), tissue.mean(IDrep))

The first row represents the mean of all data within the same time and dose bracket, excluding the repeated samples. The second row represents the samples with DOSEMGKG values and the third row represents the samples with WT & TIME values.

It appears that the row with WT & TIME has no usable concentrations. These rows were combined using the dependent variables and dose from one and the weight and time from the second.

The data should now be cleaned up and usable

Check the distribution of DV

For all data and for the mean data

meltiv <- melt(dataiv, id = c("UID", "ID", "TADNOM", "DOSEMGKG", "DOSEMG", "AMT", "WT", "TIME"))
colnames(meltiv) <- c(head(colnames(meltiv), 8), "TISSUE", "DV")
iv.distplot(meltiv, "alldata", NULL)

meltiv.av <- melt(dataiv.av, id = c("DOSEMGKG","TADNOM", "DOSEMG", "AMT", "WT", "TIME"))
colnames(meltiv.av) <- c(head(colnames(meltiv.av), 6), "TISSUE", "DV")
iv.distplot(meltiv.av, "meandata", NULL)
